## §7 — In-App FAQ Copy

*Expandable accordion. Owner can access from Screen 2*
*secondary CTA or from Settings at any time.*
*Rhythm here is direct. Read once, understand once.*

---

### Q1: What is LianaBanyan?

```
LianaBanyan is a member-owned cooperative platform for
local food businesses. Members are customers, truck owners,
builders, and creators. There is no investor class.
No one profits by extracting value from your work.
The cooperative operates under Cost+20% bylaws.
You keep 83.3% of every transaction you generate.
```
*(56 words)*

---

### Q2: Is this a coop? How is it different from a normal company?

```
Yes, a cooperative. A normal company has shareholders who
profit when costs go down and prices go up. That incentive
is the problem. This cooperative has a structural bylaw:
Cost+20% is the operating limit. Members direct the
cooperative. There is no board extracting returns.
The 50-year charter includes a dissipation clause:
if this ever dissolves, assets go to members, not founders.
```
*(70 words)*

---

### Q3: What is the $5/year for?

```
It is your membership contribution. It covers your seat
at the table as a cooperative member. It is not a
subscription fee for access to features. It is not
a deposit. It does not auto-escalate. $5/year is the
structural floor. The bylaw does not permit extracting
more from members to fund growth for investors,
because there are no investors.
```
*(61 words)*

---

### Q4: Why Cost+20%? Why not 0%?

```
Operating a payment platform, hosting infrastructure,
and member support costs real money. 0% would mean the
platform runs at a loss funded by... what? Advertising?
Investor capital? Both corrupt the incentive. Cost+20%
is honest: we recover actual costs, plus a 20% margin
to stay healthy and build. You see the math.
It does not compound to extraction.
```
*(62 words)*

---

### Q5: What happens to my customer data?

```
Customer data lives on their own machines via the
MnemosyneC local substrate. It is not sold. It is not
used for advertising. It is not on a central server
waiting to be breached or subpoenaed. The SSPL license
and cooperative charter both bind us to this.
We cannot monetize member data without a charter amendment
that members themselves would have to ratify.
```
*(65 words)*

---

### Q6: Can I leave? What happens to my customers if I do?

```
You can leave. Your membership is year-to-year; do not
renew and it lapses. Your customer relationships are yours.
We do not lock customers to your truck profile on exit.
You keep your contact list. Your order history is yours
to export. We do not hold your customers hostage
to keep you on the platform. That would be extraction.
```
*(63 words)*

---

### Q7: How does the introducer credit work?

```
When a member introduces a new member who joins,
the introducer receives a credit allocation inside the
cooperative. Credits are one of three currencies the
cooperative uses (Credits, Marks, and Joules). Credits
track contribution and participation. They are not
equity. They are not shares. They do not convert to
dollars. They make prior contribution more valuable
as the cooperative grows.
```
*(63 words)*

---

### Q8: What are Credits, Marks, and Joules?

```
Three internal currencies that track different kinds of
contribution. Credits track participation and referral.
Marks track labor and creative work. Joules track
computational work contributed to the cooperative.
None of the three convert to fiat currency. Ever.
Members get actual dollars through actual hiring and
payment for real work, not through currency conversion.
Substitution makes earlier contributions more valuable
as the cooperative grows.
```
*(69 words)*

---

### Q9: Why no VC, no ads?

```
Venture capital creates an exit incentive. The investor
needs a return. The only way to get that return is to
sell the platform or extract more value from members.
We refused that structure. Advertising creates a second
problem: members become products. We refused that too.
The cooperative is funded by Cost+20% operations.
Growth comes from member value, not from monetizing
member attention.
```
*(66 words)*

---

### Q10: Are you actually open source? Can I see the code?

```
Yes. The platform is licensed under SSPL (Server Side
Public License). The license is stricter than MIT.
If you modify and run this code as a service,
you must open source the whole stack. That means
no one can fork it into a closed competitor.
The code is publicly visible. 21 USPTO provisional
patents are filed on the underlying methodology.
Those are on record at the USPTO.
```
*(70 words)*

---

### Q11: Who runs this? Who owns it?

```
The cooperative is member-owned. The founding team
built the initial platform. As the cooperative grows,
governance passes to members through the cooperative
structure. The founding charter includes a 50-year
dissipation clause: even if the founders wanted to,
they cannot sell it to a VC or a corporation without
a member-ratified amendment. Right now, the founding
team operates it. The structure prevents capture.
```
*(66 words)*

---

### Q12: What is "Pledge #2260"?

```
Pledge #2260 is a public commitment logged in the
cooperative record. It marks a founding principle:
this platform will not be used to harm the people
it serves. The number is the pledge index in the
cooperative ledger. It is not a slogan. It is a
logged, permanent commitment that members can cite
if the cooperative ever drifts from what it said
it would be.
```
*(68 words)*

